Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Mumias Sugar, Zenith, First Bank Move

-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-03-21T17:09:39Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-21/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-mumias-sugar-zenith-first-bank-move.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index rose for the second day, adding 0.7 percent to
24,555 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to information
e-mailed by the bourse.    Kenya ’s All-Share Index fell for a third day to close at
72.71 by 3 p.m. in Nairobi, the capital. Mauritius’s SEMDEX
Index gained for the first day in seven, climbing 0.7 percent to
1,946.75 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index declined for the
first day in six, losing 1.2 percent to 1,065.3 by the 3 p.m.
close in Accra, the capital.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Mumias Sugar Co. (MSUG KN), Kenya’s biggest maker of the
sweetener, reversed earlier gains attributed by an analyst to
the start of seasonal rains and retreated for a third day to 7.7
shillings, or 0.7 percent.    Zenith Bank Plc (ZENITHBA)  , Nigeria’s second-biggest
lender by market value, and  First Bank of Nigeria Plc (FIRSTBAN)  , were among the shares of lenders in West Africa’s biggest
economy that rose after loan-loss rules were eased.  Zenith rose the most in more than three months, adding 70
kobo or the maximum daily limit of 5 percent, to 14.7 naira.
First Bank gained the most since Feb. 8, adding 64 kobo, or 5
percent, to close at 13.46 naira.  Nigeria’s Accounting Standards Board waived a rule
requiring banks to set aside cash equivalent to 1 percent of
their loans, according to a statement published today in Lagos-
based  Guardian newspaper .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eric Ombok in Nairobi at 
